{"id":"2202.04038","submitter":"Markus Lohrey","authors":"Michael Figelius and Markus Lohrey","title":"Exponent equations in HNN-extensions","comments":"Published in Journal of Groups, Complexity, Cryptology. A short\n  version appeared in Proceedings of ISSAC 2022","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider exponent equations in finitely generated groups. These are\nequations, where the variables appear as exponents of group elements and take\nvalues from the natural numbers. Solvability of such (systems of) equations has\nbeen intensively studied for various classes of groups in recent years. In many\ncases, it turns out that the set of all solutions on an exponent equation is a\nsemilinear set that can be constructed effectively. Such groups are called\nknapsack semilinear. Examples of knapsack semilinear groups are hyperbolic\ngroups, virtually special groups, co-context-free groups and free solvable\ngroups. Moreover, knapsack semilinearity is preserved by many group theoretic\nconstructions, e.g., finite extensions, graph products, wreath products,\namalgamated free products with finite amalgamated subgroups, and HNN-extensions\nwith finite associated subgroups. On the other hand, arbitrary HNN-extensions\ndo not preserve knapsack semilinearity. In this paper, we consider the knapsack\nsemilinearity of HNN-extensions, where the stable letter $t$ acts trivially by\nconjugation on the associated subgroup $A$ of the base group $G$. We show that\nunder some additional technical conditions, knapsack semilinearity transfers\nfrom base group $G$ to the HNN-extension $H$. These additional technical\nconditions are satisfied in many cases, e.g., when $A$ is a centralizer in $G$\nor $A$ is a quasiconvex subgroup of the hyperbolic group $G$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 8 Feb 2022 18:07:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 23 Sep 2022 17:39:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 20 Dec 2022 14:59:29 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 23 Dec 2022 10:00:58 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 26 Dec 2022 15:17:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-27"}
