{"id":"2202.04279","submitter":"Jianguo Qian","authors":"Lu Fuliang and Qian Jianguo","title":"Removable edges in cubic matching covered graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An edge $e$ in a matching covered graph $G$ is removable if $G-e$ is matching\ncovered, which was introduced by Lov\\'asz and Plummer in connection with ear\ndecompositions of matching covered graphs. A brick is a non-bipartite matching\ncovered graph without non-trivial tight cuts. The importance of bricks stems\nfrom the fact that they are building blocks of matching covered graphs.\nCarvalho et al. [Ear decompositions of matching covered graphs, Combinatorica,\n19(2):151-174, 1999] showed that each brick other than $K_4$ and\n$\\overline{C_6}$ has $\\Delta-2$ removable edges, where $\\Delta$ is the maximum\ndegree of $G$. We show that every cubic brick $G$ other than $K_4$,\n$\\overline{C_6}$ and a particular graph of order 8 has a matching of size at\nleast $|V(G)|/7$, each edge of which is removable in $G$. Moreover, if $G$ is a\n3-edge-connected near-bipartite cubic graph, then $G$ has a matching of size at\nleast $|V(G)|/2-3$, each edge of which is removable in $G$. The lower bounds\nfor the two sizes of matchings are sharp.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Feb 2022 04:53:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-10"}
